{
  "texts": [
    "For example, as illustrated in table 5, the indirect bounds on C (unconstrained by the EW sector at tree-level) obtains the most stringent constraint from the Z-pole observable A FB b due to its RG mixing into the flavor-universal O HD (see figure 1).",
    "The second important point is the relevance of going beyond the LL approximation when solving the RG equations.",
    "Even though the scale hierarchy we deal with is not particularly large, next-to-leading log (NLL) effects yield corrections as large as 30% to the LL results, which inadvertedly tend to relax the LL constraints.",
    "A particularly interesting case is that of O Although it is parameterically a two-loop effect, this NLL running can be sizeable, as pointed out in [35], leading to a bound of 1.2 TeV on C[3333] uu.",
    "Surprisingly, this purely NLL running into a Z-pole observable results in a more stringent constraint on this operator than direct collider searches, which yield a bound of about 800 GeV.Lastly, it is worth stressing that in selected observables, one-loop matching from the SMEFT to the LEFT can be crucial in order to obtain the correct low-energy phenomenology."
  ]
